Penetration Testing and Machine Learning-Driven Cybersecurity Framework for IoT and Smart City Wireless Networks

Author: Aathila Fathima
Department of Computer Science
B.Tech Final Year Project

Abstract

The rapid expansion of Internet of Things (IoT) technologies has significantly transformed smart city infrastructures by enabling intelligent services such as traffic management, smart surveillance, environmental monitoring, and energy optimization. However, the large-scale deployment of IoT devices introduces serious cybersecurity challenges due to limited device security, heterogeneous communication protocols, and increased attack surfaces. Traditional security solutions are often insufficient to detect sophisticated network attacks targeting IoT environments.

This research proposes a machine learning-driven cybersecurity framework for IoT and smart city wireless networks. The system integrates intrusion detection, penetration testing, real-time traffic monitoring, and visualization through a Security Operations Center (SOC) dashboard. A Random Forest machine learning model is trained to analyze network traffic features and classify malicious activities. The framework also includes a port scanning module to detect vulnerable services in IoT devices and a graphical dashboard for monitoring network activity.

Experimental results show that the proposed system achieves detection accuracy above 95%, demonstrating its effectiveness in identifying malicious network behavior. The proposed framework improves cybersecurity monitoring and provides a proactive defense mechanism for smart city IoT networks.

Keywords

IoT Security, Intrusion Detection System, Machine Learning, Smart City Networks, Cybersecurity Framework, Penetration Testing

1. Introduction

The Internet of Things (IoT) has become a fundamental component of modern smart city infrastructures. IoT devices such as sensors, smart meters, surveillance cameras, and traffic monitoring systems enable automated data collection and intelligent decision-making. These devices communicate continuously through wireless networks to provide efficient urban services.

Despite these benefits, IoT networks are highly vulnerable to cyber attacks. Many IoT devices have limited processing capabilities and weak security configurations, making them attractive targets for attackers. Cyber attacks such as Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS), botnet attacks, port scanning, and brute force attacks can compromise IoT networks and disrupt smart city services.

Traditional cybersecurity systems rely on rule-based detection mechanisms that cannot effectively identify unknown or evolving threats. Machine learning techniques provide a promising solution by analyzing network traffic patterns and detecting anomalies.

This research introduces a cybersecurity framework that combines machine learning intrusion detection, penetration testing, and real-time monitoring through an interactive dashboard. The system aims to improve the detection of malicious activities and enhance the security of IoT-based smart city networks.

2. Related Work

Several studies have investigated intrusion detection systems for IoT environments using machine learning techniques. Researchers have explored algorithms such as Support Vector Machines (SVM), Decision Trees, Random Forests, and Neural Networks to classify network traffic patterns.

Datasets such as UNSW-NB15, CICIoT2023, and TON-IoT are commonly used for evaluating network intrusion detection models. These datasets contain network traffic records representing both normal and malicious activities.

Many existing intrusion detection systems focus solely on attack detection without providing real-time visualization or vulnerability assessment capabilities. In contrast, our proposed framework integrates machine learning detection, penetration testing through port scanning, and a SOC dashboard to provide a complete cybersecurity monitoring solution.

3. System Architecture

The proposed system architecture consists of multiple components working together to monitor and secure IoT networks.

The architecture includes the following modules:

• IoT Device Layer
• Network Traffic Monitoring
• Feature Extraction
• Machine Learning Intrusion Detection System
• Penetration Testing Module
• Security Operations Center Dashboard

IoT devices generate network traffic that is monitored by the system. Packet data is captured and processed to extract relevant network features such as packet size, protocol type, connection duration, and packet count.

The extracted features are then analyzed using a trained Random Forest machine learning model to classify traffic as normal or malicious. If an attack is detected, the system generates alerts through the SOC dashboard.

Additionally, the penetration testing module performs port scanning to identify open services on network devices, allowing administrators to detect potential vulnerabilities.


