4. Methodology

The proposed cybersecurity framework follows a multi-stage methodology.

4.1 Dataset Generation

A simulated IoT network dataset containing approximately 50,000 network traffic samples was generated. Each record contains multiple features representing network communication characteristics.

The dataset includes both normal traffic and malicious traffic patterns.

4.2 Data Preprocessing

Data preprocessing is performed to prepare the dataset for machine learning training.

Key preprocessing steps include:

• Removing missing values
• Encoding categorical features such as protocol type and service type
• Splitting the dataset into training and testing sets

Label encoding is applied to convert textual network attributes into numerical values.

4.3 Machine Learning Model

A Random Forest classifier is used for intrusion detection. Random Forest is an ensemble learning algorithm that constructs multiple decision trees and combines their predictions.

Advantages of Random Forest include:

• High classification accuracy
• Robustness against overfitting
• Ability to handle large datasets

The model is trained using 80% of the dataset and evaluated using the remaining 20%.

4.4 Penetration Testing Module

The penetration testing module performs port scanning to identify open services on network devices. Common ports such as HTTP, SSH, FTP, and HTTPS are checked.

By detecting open ports, administrators can identify potentially vulnerable services that may be exploited by attackers.

4.5 SOC Dashboard Visualization

A graphical Security Operations Center (SOC) dashboard is developed using Python and Tkinter. The dashboard provides real-time monitoring of network security.

The dashboard includes the following features:

• Attack detection interface
• Port scanning results table
• Network traffic visualization graph
• IoT device monitoring panel
• Automatic security alerts


